    "# Lane 3: Structured Content Archetype Clustering\n",
    "## FlyRank ML Internship — Week 1–2 Framing Notebook\n",
    "\n",
    "**Status:** Lane choice, research question, and real data evidence.  \n",
    "**Author:** Krithika-Sulochana-08  \n",
    "**Date:** 2026-07-15  \n",
    "**Confidence:** Confirmed for Weeks 1–4 review; may pivot by end of Week 4."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 1. Research Question\n",
    "\n",
    "**What distinct performance archetypes exist across the content inventory, and which actions (protect, improve, rewrite, merge, prune, monitor) should apply to each?**\n",
    "\n",
    "### Justification\n",
    "\n",
    "One-size-fits-all refreshment strategies fail because content behaves very differently. Some pages are:\n",
    "- **Champions:** high impressions, strong CTR, good engagement — protect and monitor.\n",
    "- **Rising stars:** growing visibility but low engagement — improve on-page experience.\n",
    "- **Hidden gems:** low visibility despite good engagement — promote or fix metadata.\n",
    "- **Stale visible pages:** old, high impression, declining — refresh urgently.\n",
    "- **Weak/no-demand pages:** low impressions, no growth signal — consider pruning.\n",
    "\n",
    "By identifying these archetypes empirically from the data, I can recommend tailored actions that are more likely to succeed than generic scoring. This is **not just training a model**—it's building a framework for content triage that reviewers can understand, inspect, and act on."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 2. Unit of Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "**One row = one unique content piece (page), identified by `content_id`.**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Grain:** Content-level snapshot within the last 90 days.\n",
    "- **Filters:** Must have `impressions_90d >= 1` to avoid noise.\n",
    "- **No time series:** This is a single-window snapshot; each page gets one archetype label.\n",
    "- **Client diversity:** The dataset spans multiple clients, so archetypes should hold across clients (or with client-level breakdowns if they diverge)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 3. Decision & Action\n",
    "\n",
    "### Decision\n",
    "\n",
    "**\"Assign this content to one of 5–7 archetypes and recommend a specific action lane.\"**\n",
    "\n",
    "### Action Someone Takes\n",
    "\n",
    "A content manager or SEO reviewer looks at the archetype label and reason codes (e.g., *\"Hidden Gem: high engagement (70% scroll), 150 impressions, 0.8K sessions, but only 12 days old — improve SEO reach\"*) and decides:\n",
    "- **Champions:** Monitor monthly; protect from accidental deletions or restructuring.\n",
    "- **Rising stars:** Run A/B tests on metadata or CTA.\n",
    "- **Hidden gems:** Boost SEO signals (backlinks, internal linking, schema markup).\n",
    "- **Stale visible pages:** Refresh content, update examples, verify claims.\n",
    "- **Weak/no-demand:** Audit intent fit or consider consolidation.\n",
    "- **Engagement problems:** Improve on-page UX (speed, clarity, formatting).\n",
    "- **Cannibalization risk:** Merge or redirect related URLs.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is actionable because each archetype comes with specific next steps, not a black-box score."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 4. Output & Deliverable\n",
    "\n",
    "### Output\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Cluster profiles:** For each archetype, 3–5 defining metrics (mean impressions, CTR, engagement rate, age, trend).\n",
    "- **Archetype names & descriptions:** Human-readable labels (\"Champions,\" \"Rising Stars,\" etc.).\n",
    "- **Action mapping:** For each archetype, a recommended action (or set of actions) and reason codes.\n",
    "- **Data viz:** 2D projection (PCA or t-SNE) showing cluster separation and overlap; radar chart of archetype profiles.\n",
    "- **Case examples:** Top 3 examples per archetype with pseudonymized IDs, key metrics, and recommended action.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Format\n",
    "\n",
    "- Jupyter notebook with reproducible pipeline (scale → cluster → profile → export).\n",
    "- CSV export: `content_id`, `archetype`, `confidence`, `reason_codes` for review queuing.\n",
    "- One-page summary: archetype profiles, sizing, and action volume.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Public Safety\n",
    "\n",
    "- ✅ Pseudonymized content IDs and client IDs.\n",
    "- ✅ Aggregated metrics (mean, median, counts per archetype).\n",
    "- ✅ Generic action recommendations (no client names or URLs).\n",
    "- ❌ No raw domains, titles, or query examples.\n",
    "- ❌ No claims about Google algorithm factors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 5. Cost of Wrong Recommendations & Why ML Helps\n",
    "\n",
    "### Cost of Being Wrong\n",
    "\n",
    "**High:** If a \"Stale Visible Page\" is misclassified as a \"Hidden Gem,\" the team spends effort on SEO optimization when they should have refreshed the content. Conversely, if a \"Rising Star\" is flagged for pruning, the team loses a high-potential page.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Opportunity cost:** With limited review capacity (maybe 50–100 pages/week), mislabeling wastes the highest-ROI actions and leaves true problems unfixed.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why Data & ML Help\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Manual bucketing fails at scale:** With 500+ content items across multiple clients, eyeballing archetypes is slow, inconsistent, and biased toward recent or visible pages.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Multi-dimensional patterns:** Archetypes depend on combinations of signals (impressions + CTR + engagement + age + trend), not single thresholds. Clustering finds these patterns automatically.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Stability & repeatability:** Once trained, the clustering pipeline can be rerun monthly or quarterly. New pages are automatically assigned to the archetype they most resemble.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Explainability matters:** Unlike a black-box score, cluster centroids and reason codes can be inspected. Reviewers can audit why a page is in a cluster and push back if it doesn't match their domain knowledge.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. **Signal audit:** The clustering process forces me to define which signals matter (impressions, CTR, engagement, freshness, trend) and how they interact—a data-driven alternative to guesswork."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 6. Real Numbers from Starter Dataset"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load the starter dataset\n",
    "df = pd.read_csv('../data/raw/content_refresh_anonymized.csv')\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Dataset shape:\", df.shape)\n",
    "print(\"\\nFirst few rows:\")\n",
    "print(df.head())\n",
    "print(\"\\nColumn names:\")\n",
    "print(df.columns.tolist())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Finding 1: Signal Diversity Across Content\n",
    "\n",
    "Content pages vary dramatically in visibility, engagement, and freshness—a strong signal that archetypes exist."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Filter for rows with at least 1 impression to remove noise\n",
    "df_valid = df[df['impressions_90d'] >= 1].copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Rows with impressions_90d >= 1: {len(df_valid)} out of {len(df)} ({100*len(df_valid)/len(df):.1f}%)\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nImpression distribution (90d):\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Mean:     {df_valid['impressions_90d'].mean():.0f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Median:   {df_valid['impressions_90d'].median():.0f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Min:      {df_valid['impressions_90d'].min():.0f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Max:      {df_valid['impressions_90d'].max():.0f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Std dev:  {df_valid['impressions_90d'].std():.0f}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\nCTR distribution (where defined):\")\n",
    "df_valid_ctr = df_valid[df_valid['ctr'].notna()]\n",
    "print(f\"  Mean:     {df_valid_ctr['ctr'].mean():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Median:   {df_valid_ctr['ctr'].median():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Min:      {df_valid_ctr['ctr'].min():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Max:      {df_valid_ctr['ctr'].max():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Rows with CTR:  {len(df_valid_ctr)} / {len(df_valid)}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\nEngagement rate distribution (where defined):\")\n",
    "df_valid_eng = df_valid[df_valid['engagement_rate'].notna()]\n",
    "print(f\"  Mean:     {df_valid_eng['engagement_rate'].mean():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Median:   {df_valid_eng['engagement_rate'].median():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Min:      {df_valid_eng['engagement_rate'].min():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Max:      {df_valid_eng['engagement_rate'].max():.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Rows with engagement_rate: {len(df_valid_eng)} / {len(df_valid)}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\nContent age (days):\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Mean:     {df_valid['content_age_days'].mean():.0f} days\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Median:   {df_valid['content_age_days'].median():.0f} days\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Min:      {df_valid['content_age_days'].min():.0f} days\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Max:      {df_valid['content_age_days'].max():.0f} days\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Finding 2: Clustering Is Justified by Multimodal Distributions\n",
    "\n",
    "The distribution of content across impressions and engagement is multimodal—some pages have high impressions and high CTR (\"Champions\"), others have high impressions but low CTR (\"Stale\"), and others have low impressions regardless. This multimodality is a textbook case for clustering."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Group by impression tier and engagement to show multimodality\n",
    "df_valid['impression_tier'] = pd.cut(df_valid['impressions_90d'], \n",
    "                                       bins=[0, 100, 500, 5000, float('inf')],\n",
    "                                       labels=['Low (1-100)', 'Medium (100-500)', 'High (500-5K)', 'Very High (5K+)'])\n",
    "\n",
    "df_valid['ctr_tier'] = pd.cut(df_valid['ctr'], \n",
    "                                bins=[-np.inf, 0.02, 0.05, 0.10, np.inf],\n",
    "                                labels=['Very Low (<2%)', 'Low (2-5%)', 'Medium (5-10%)', 'High (10%+)'])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Cross-tabulation\n",
    "cross_tab = pd.crosstab(df_valid['impression_tier'], df_valid['ctr_tier'], margins=True)\n",
    "print(\"Pages by Impression Tier × CTR Tier (count):\")\n",
    "print(cross_tab)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nTotal valid pages: {len(df_valid)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Finding 3: Trend Signal Shows Content Movement\n",
    "\n",
    "The `trend_direction` field captures whether content is growing, stable, or declining—a key archetype signal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "trend_counts = df_valid['trend_direction'].value_counts()\n",
    "print(\"Content by Trend Direction:\")\n",
    "print(trend_counts)\n",
    "print(f\"\\nPercentages:\")\n",
    "for trend, count in trend_counts.items():\n",
    "    pct = 100 * count / len(df_valid)\n",
    "    print(f\"  {trend}: {count} ({pct:.1f}%)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Finding 4: Archetype Sketch from Simple Rules\n",
    "\n",
    "Let me sketch rough archetypes using simple rules to show that distinct groups exist in the data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create rough archetype buckets using simple rules\n",
    "# (This is NOT the final clustering; it's just to show diversity exists)\n",
    "\n",
    "def sketch_archetype(row):\n",
    "    imp = row['impressions_90d']\n",
    "    ctr = row.get('ctr', np.nan)\n",
    "    eng = row.get('engagement_rate', np.nan)\n",
    "    trend = row.get('trend_direction', '')\n",
    "    age = row.get('content_age_days', 0)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Handle missing CTR/engagement\n",
    "    if pd.isna(ctr):\n",
    "        ctr = 0\n",
    "    if pd.isna(eng):\n",
    "        eng = 0\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Simple rules\n",
    "    if imp >= 1000 and ctr >= 0.05:\n",
    "        return 'Champion'\n",
    "    elif imp >= 500 and trend == 'up':\n",
    "        return 'Rising_Star'\n",
    "    elif imp < 200 and eng >= 0.5:\n",
    "        return 'Hidden_Gem'\n",
    "    elif imp >= 500 and trend == 'down':\n",
    "        return 'Stale_Visible'\n",
    "    elif imp < 100:\n",
    "        return 'Weak_Demand'\n",
    "    elif eng > 0 and eng < 0.3 and imp >= 500:\n",
    "        return 'Engagement_Problem'\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return 'Other'\n",
    "\n",
    "df_valid['sketch_archetype'] = df_valid.apply(sketch_archetype, axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Rough Archetype Distribution (from simple rules):\")\n",
    "archetype_counts = df_valid['sketch_archetype'].value_counts()\n",
    "for arch, count in archetype_counts.items():\n",
    "    pct = 100 * count / len(df_valid)\n",
    "    print(f\"  {arch}: {count:3d} ({pct:5.1f}%)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\nThis shows that archetypes DO exist and are reasonably sized:\")\n",
    "print(f\"  - Champions + Rising Stars = {(archetype_counts.get('Champion', 0) + archetype_counts.get('Rising_Star', 0)) / len(df_valid) * 100:.1f}% (high priority)\")\n",
    "print(f\"  - Stale / Weak = {(archetype_counts.get('Stale_Visible', 0) + archetype_counts.get('Weak_Demand', 0)) / len(df_valid) * 100:.1f}% (needs action)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Finding 5: Profile Variation Within Archetypes\n",
    "\n",
    "Even with simple rules, archetypes have distinct profiles—proof that clustering can find meaningful structure."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Show mean profiles by archetype\n",
    "print(\"\\nMean Metrics by Archetype (simple rule sketch):\")\n",
    "print(\"=\"*80)\n",
    "\n",
    "for arch in ['Champion', 'Rising_Star', 'Hidden_Gem', 'Stale_Visible', 'Weak_Demand']:\n",
    "    subset = df_valid[df_valid['sketch_archetype'] == arch]\n",
    "    if len(subset) == 0:\n",
    "        continue\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(f\"\\n{arch}:\")\n",
    "    print(f\"  Count: {len(subset)} pages\")\n",
    "    print(f\"  Mean impressions: {subset['impressions_90d'].mean():.0f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"  Mean CTR: {subset['ctr'].mean():.3f} (where available)\")\n",
    "    print(f\"  Mean engagement: {subset['engagement_rate'].mean():.3f} (where available)\")\n",
    "    print(f\"  Mean age (days): {subset['content_age_days'].mean():.0f}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"  Trend: {subset['trend_direction'].value_counts().to_dict()}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7. Why This Is Not \"Just Training a Model\"\n",
    "\n",
    "This project goes beyond fitting a clustering algorithm:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Interpretability first:** Each archetype must be explainable in business terms. I'm not optimizing for silhouette score; I'm optimizing for actionability. Reviewers need to understand why a page is in a cluster.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Signal audit:** The choice of features (impressions, CTR, engagement, age, trend) is deliberate, not automatic. I'll test whether each signal adds value and document which archetypes rely on which signals.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Action mapping:** The output is not cluster membership; it's a specific, labeled action (\"refresh this page,\" \"protect this page,\" \"improve engagement\"). The clustering is a means to an end.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Validation by review:** I'll validate archetypes by asking: \"Do people agree that pages in this cluster should get the same action?\" Silhouette score doesn't answer that question.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. **Iterative refinement:** If a cluster doesn't produce coherent actions (e.g., high-variance archetypes with conflicting next steps), I'll re-cluster or adjust features rather than accept the model output as truth.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is **framework design, not just modeling**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 8. Timeline & Milestones (Weeks 1–7)\n",
