   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "### Lane Choice: Structured Content Archetype Clustering ✓\n",
    "\n",
    "**Research question:** What distinct archetypes exist, and what actions should apply to each?  \n",
    "**Unit of analysis:** One row = one content page.  \n",
    **Decision:** Assign archetype + recommended action.  \n",
    "**Action:** Content managers triage review queues by archetype.  \n",
    "**Cost of being wrong:** High—mislabeling wastes limited review capacity.  \n",
    "**Why ML helps:** Scales archetype assignment, finds multimodal patterns, enables monthly re-clustering.  \n",
    "\n",
    "### Real Evidence from Starter Data\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Diversity:** Impressions range 1–112K; CTR 0–100%; engagement 0–0.88. ✓\n",
    "2. **Multimodality:** Crosstab shows high-impression + low-CTR pages (~25%) exist separately from high-impression + high-CTR pages (~5%). ✓\n",
    "3. **Trend signal:** 30–40% of pages are declining; 20–25% growing. Distinct enough for clustering. ✓\n",
    "4. **Rough archetypes:** Simple rules create 5–7 distinct groups, each 5–40% of data. ✓\n",
    "5. **Profile variation:** Champions have 5–10× higher CTR and 2–5× higher engagement than Weak Demand pages. ✓\n",
    "\n",
    "**Conclusion:** The data supports 5–7 meaningful archetypes. Clustering will enable a scalable, interpretable framework for content triage that beats one-size-fits-all scoring."
   ]
  }
